text: hi everyone hath aniline tan oh here the
Internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new Phoebe
Bridgers album Punisher this is the
second full-length album from
singer-songwriter Phoebe Bridgers who
has become quite the commodity in the
indie scene over the past couple of
years her breakout debut led immediately
to a critically acclaimed collaboration
with Lucy Dacus and Julian Baker then
from there she went on to an entire set
of co-written songs with the great Conor
Oberst of bright eyes Fame Phoebe has
been having quite the run and she seems
to be extending it with her sophomore LP
which i think is her best project yet
now as the teaser tracks from this album
were rolling in I do admit I wasn't
thinking that this was going to be that
immense of an album they weren't doing
all that much for me starting out it was
difficult to hear what exactly made
punisher such a special listen it is an
incredibly understated and subtle record
and Phoebe doesn't exactly have the
boldest or most in your face singing
voice some of the instrumentals do run
like boilerplate indie rock and folk as
well like the track Kyoto while the
horns laced into this track are legit
gorgeous the driving somewhat garage
guitars and drums are as plain as can be
but the more I began to listen to this
album the more the emotion of it the
sadness of it began to hit me like a
Mack truck
it is stunning how emotionally crushing
some points of this album are to the
point where what Phoebe is doing here
reminds me of some Elliot Smith with her
vocal lines her devotion to nuance as
well as her tragic and smart lyricism
and despite my reservations on a few
tracks there actually is some
interesting production to be had in the
tracklist here the track
garden song features these filtered
kicks and bass and watery guitars it's
all very muddy but it's not muddy in the
way that a badly produced album would
sound muddy there is a surreal
dreaminess to the way the
instrumentation is treated on this track
once again I get this feeling of being
submerged slowly and this feeling is
enhanced by lines like it must be
something in the water
then on top of this it is Phoebe's quiet
but haunting voice singing chilling
bittersweet melodies and lyrics that
seem to be about a lot of things but
mostly various points of Phoebe's life
rolling past her like she's having an
out-of-body experience and she's
watching them like they're a movie the
emotion she draws out of this experience
manifesting in a very intense way we
have the title track as well which is
equally dreamy surreal and devastating
the subtle ghostly and melodic vocal
manipulations on Phoebe singing are
fantastic they add a lot of character
the serene piano arpeggios along with
these detailed fluttering beautiful
little string arrangements are a nice
touch to this track also features one of
the most enchanting choruses on the
entire record and going into this it's
kind of funny that I immediately picked
up on the massive Elias Smith influence
on multiple tracks here just right away
because I guess the lyrics of the song
are kind of about obsessing over him
with Phoebe painting herself as a
Punisher or someone who's just obsessed
with something to the point that they're
talking about it over and over and over
and endlessly they just don't know when
to stop which I suppose is an
interesting thing to put out in a song
not just from a personal perspective but
it's a reminder that musicians get into
music because they are fans of music and
they are fans of the people who make
music and most likely the biggest
artists out there all have someone they
look up to and idolize and wish they
could be or just live up to the track
Halloween is emotionally cutting as well
but for different reasons
the plucky gentle harmonious and sweet
Baroque instrumentation reminds me of a
mountain goat song or two Thumb Attica
Lee the lyrics explore the concept of
Halloween as a means of doing or being
something different with lines like but
I can count on you to tell me the truth
when you've been drinking and you're
wearing a mask so this can mean you're
being more real or more honest than you
would normally be but also of something
else entirely something just to fit the
needs of others around you at least
that's how I read it the following track
Chinese satellite has some respectable
qualities as well one of Phoebe's bolder

voice really soaring over the
instrumentation but as the song
progresses the strings the guitars the
Ace the drums I'll get more and more

an ear sore then I'm somewhat

connection or relationship that from

kind of doomed from the start
overall it's a very sad swaying ballad
in 3/4 that runs a very predictable
course by comparison savior complex is a
lot more hard-hitting emotionally but
from the chord progression to the
massive shows of drama in the lyrics
like wake up and start a big fire in our

have a pissing contest this song is just
so Elliott Smith it's buried in the DNA
which I guess as long as the song is
good is not something I mind too much
because up until this point that
influence continues to manifest itself
in Phoebe's music in interesting ways
plus the instrumental is great
especially with that gorgeous string
section on the bridge which is altered
very interestingly the way the
background instrumentation is filtered
and gets louder and more bright as we
near the end of the bridge there are a
lot of interesting uses of EQ and again
filters all over this record we then
have a strong finish for the record with
the very punchy I see you thunderous

head-bobbing groove cathartic rushes of
instrumentation that are perfectly
placed in this tracklist after all this
sad tension Jesus did we need some
release the lyrics aren't exactly
uplifting on this one Phoebe is talking
about [ __ ] things up essentially here
one of the saddest lines of the song
being that when she feels good she fears
it will be the last time she feels good
with the second-to-last track we get a
lot of plucky full instrumentation sound
tracking a story of what sounds like a
girl being free unencumbered able to get
out there as she pleases but the opening
line of no longer being a danger to
herself and others kind of implies that
she is transitioning out of a place
where maybe she was held in a spot not
able to do as he pleased
gorgeous vocal harmonies on the hook as
well and then there is the closer which
instrumentally is a grand finale with
this amazing crescendo
horns and crashing rock instrumentation
even Phoebe screaming her brains out it
sounds like some Arcade Fire or some
Beirut [ __ ] until it turns like
supremely sour and distorted and evil I
like to see it as this song just kind of
tying up a lot of things the matically
on this record because it touches down
on so many familiar ideas from previous
songs there is this sense of freedom and
weightlessness about this track but also
a supreme sense of existential dread
overall I don't have a lot about this
record I didn't like I think it's a
strong showing from Bridgers quality
songs instrumentals performances sure
there were a few underwhelming tracks
and could she do with a bit less wearing
her influences on her sleeve maybe but
still the emotional potency of this
record is undeniable and that's really
what ended up selling it for me feeling
